Some experts believe that the low number of people tested is the reason for the low number of confirmed cases in the United States.



The first suspected case of community-acquired pneumonia has alerted the United States, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has revised its criteria. But since the first case was confirmed on January 21, the U. S. epidemic prevention efforts have been met with much skepticism.

CDC Director Redfield said Monday that the CDC has issued new guidelines for the detection of coronaviruses. According to the new standards, patients with fever and severe lower respiratory tract infection symptoms can be tested even without a history of exposure, ruling out influenza and other respiratory disease. Under previous tests, patients would need to have a history of travel to China or close contact with a confirmed patient, in addition to symptoms.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image Credit: CDC. com

As a result, testing for the first suspected case of community-transmitted disease in the United States has been delayed by four days.

February 26, a woman from Solano County, California confirmed the infection, but the path of infection is unknown, may be the first case of community-based transmission in the United States. The patient developed new symptoms of coronary pneumonia on Feb. 19, when doctors ordered a viral test but put it on hold because she did not meet the criteria. The CDC did not test the patient until 23, at the doctor's insistence, and confirmed the test on 26. It had been a full week since the patient had been admitted to hospital.

But the CDC said it did not receive a report until the 23rd to test a sample of the patient and is investigating the incident. The CDC also acknowledged that patients could be diagnosed earlier under the new test.

The patient is being treated at the University of California, Davis at Sacramento County. California Senator John Garamendi told the CNN that the patient was in a serious condition and had been intubated.

The patient's family and staff who had close contact with him were tested and are being quarantined at home.

A student at University of California, Davis, who is also at risk of exposure to the virus, has been tested for nucleic acids and is being quarantined at home. Yolo County, Calif. , health officials said the student's nasal and throat swabs would be sent to the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta for testing, and no results would be available for several days. His two roommate, also in school isolation, showed no symptoms. The university's medical centre is not on campus and is about 27 km away. It is not clear whether the student had contact with the above-mentioned confirmed patient.

In addition, the CDC will also Iran, Italy, South Korea and Japan are included in the focus of countries. Passengers arriving from these countries are required to undergo a medical examination at the airport.

The supply of nucleic acid detection kits is also an important factor affecting the detection efficiency. The CDC announced the Kit last month, and earlier this month it received authorization to distribute it to public health laboratories in 50 states, the Associated Press reported. However, the CDC admitted on the 26th, most of these kits have defects, detection results are not accurate.

The CDC said it was working on a new version of the kit, but it was unclear when it would be available. As of the beginning of this week, laboratories in only six states had access to effective kits. California Governor Newson (Gavin Newsom) said 27, the State is currently about 8,400 people under medical observation, but only 200 kits.

New Coronaviruses are typically tested in three steps, with the third step causing problems, so 40 laboratories are now licensed by the Federal Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to use the first two steps of an existing kit to make a diagnosis.

In addition, all test samples need to be sent to the federal testing center, further prolonging the diagnostic time. By the end of the week, the number of testing-capable laboratories in the country is expected to grow to 93, with 70 companies racing to develop "clinical diagnostic" tests, said Alex Azar, secretary of the US Department of Health and Human Services.

Adjara Autonomous Republic said on the 27th that only about 3,600 people across the country had been tested. Some experts believe that the low number of tests may be the reason for the low number of confirmed cases in the United States.

Although the first case of an unknown source of infection sent jitters across the country, President Donald Trump, who repeatedly stressed at a White House press conference the day before that the new pneumonia was nothing more than a flu like illness, remained highly optimistic. He said at the event on the 27th, the United States has done a good job in combating the new crown disease, one day the virus will miraculously disappear. Analysts at Goldman Sachs have warned that Donald Trump could lose this year's election if stock markets continue to fall on COVID-19.

Separately, two officials told Reuters that the Donald Trump administration was considering using special powers in the defense production act to rapidly expand production of protective gear such as face masks, gloves and protective clothing. By law, the president has the power to expand the production of key materials and products in demand for reasons of national security and other reasons. 3m and Honeyville, two of the world's leading mask makers, are American.

Adjara Autonomous Republic said demand for N95 masks in the US was about 300m, but only 12m were currently in stock and another 5m were not certified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (Niosh) because they were out of date.

The president's endorsement of the epidemic does not seem to have gone down well. A woman from HHS, the source said, more than a dozen personnel involved in the evacuation of Wuhan personnel in the process of lack of proper training and protection measures. None of the workers showed symptoms of a suspected infection, nor were they placed under quarantine or tested for a new coronavirus, the source said. The whistle-blower also said he had been forced to change jobs for no reason after raising the concern and was seeking protection.

According to The Washington Post, the workers are from the Department of Health and Human Services'children and Families Agency (ACF) . People familiar with the situation said the staff members were not tested for the new coronavirus because they did not meet the test criteria.

Frieden, a former CDC director, declined to comment on the revelation, but he repeatedly stressed that the new coronavirus would spread more widely in the United States. Frieden believes that the new pneumonia is bound to become a global "pandemic" , but how serious is unknown.

The United States Department of Homeland Security, on its disaster preparedness website, urged people to prepare for the epidemic, including stockpiling two weeks'worth of food and water and regularly checking their homes for conventional and over the counter drugs.

So far, there have been 60 confirmed cases in the United States, of which 3 were Americans recently evacuated from Wuhan, 42 were passengers of the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship, and 14 had personal or close contacts with travel history in China, the route of infection was unknown in one case.
